  "prompt": "What will happen to the border between Northern Ireland and Ireland following the Brexit vote?",
  "response": "After the Brexit vote, the border between Northern Ireland (part of the UK) and the Republic of Ireland (an EU member state) became a complex issue. To avoid a hard border with physical infrastructure, the Northern Ireland Protocol was implemented as part of the Brexit withdrawal agreement. Under this protocol:\n\n1. Northern Ireland effectively remains part of the EU's single market for goods, maintaining an open border with Ireland.\n\n2. Some customs and regulatory checks are conducted on goods moving between Great Britain and Northern Ireland, creating a de facto border in the Irish Sea.\n\n3. This arrangement aims to prevent a hard border on the island of Ireland, which could potentially disrupt the peace established by the Good Friday Agreement.\n\n4. The protocol has been controversial, with some unionists in Northern Ireland opposing the additional checks and perceived separation from the rest of the UK.\n\n5. Ongoing negotiations and adjustments have continued to refine the implementation of the protocol.\n\nThe goal has been to maintain an open border between Northern Ireland and Ireland while addressing Brexit's economic and regulatory implications.",
